04579nam a22004935i 9780520927407DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20022003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209274077 a10.1525/97805209274072doi  a(DE-B1597)519122  a(OCoLC)52842619  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aNAT0110002bisacsh0481pa333.72092221/oclc1 aDasmann, Raymond, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCalled by the Wild :bThe Autobiography of a Conservationist /cRaymond Dasmann. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (270 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. Beginnings: The Lure of Wild Country -- t2. School, the Woods, and War -- t3. Red Arrows Never Glance -- t4. Live Coward or Dead Hero? -- t5. Elizabeth's Story -- t6. Reunion -- t7. Transition -- t8. Deer -- t9. Arcata -- t10. Conservation by Slaughter -- t11. Return to the United States -- t12. Influences and Efforts -- t13. Too Many, Too Much -- t14. Uniting Nations -- t15. Return to Africa -- t16. Ecosystem and Biosphere People -- t17. The Edges of the Sea -- t18. The Incident in Kinshasha -- t19. Return to the South Pacific -- t20. Back to the Land -- t21. Damming Paradise -- t22. Other Ways of Life -- t23. Biosphere Reserves -- t24. Finale -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA pioneer in international conservation and wildlife ecology, Raymond Dasmann published his first book, the influential text Environmental Conservation, when the term "environment" was little known and "conservation" to most people simply meant keeping or storing. This delightful memoir tells the story of an unpretentious man who helped create and shape today's environmental movement. Ranging from Dasmann's travels to ecological hotspots around the world to his development of concepts such as bioregionalism and ecotourism, this autobiography is a story of international conservation action and intrigue, a moving love story, and a gripping chronicle of an exceptional life.Dasmann takes us from his boyhood days in San Francisco in the early 1920s to his action-packed military service in Australia during World War II, where he met his future wife, Elizabeth. After returning to the United States, Dasmann received his doctorate as a conservation biologist when the field was just being developed. Dasmann left the safety of academia to work with conservation organizations around the world, including the United Nations, and has done fieldwork in Africa, Sri Lanka, the Caribbean, and California.This book is both a memoir and an account of how Dasmann's thinking developed around issues that are vitally important today. In engaging conversational language, he shares his thoughts on issues he has grappled with throughout his life, such as population growth and the question of how sustainability can be measured, understood, and regained. Called by the Wild tells the story of an inspirational risk taker who reminds us that "the earth is the only known nature reserve in the entire universe" and that we must learn to treat it as such.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927407423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520927407.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978